Parliament does not support an amendment giving Tymoshenko freedom
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in the course of the amendments to the Code of Criminal Procedure, has rejected an attempt to repeal an article that condemned the leader of the opposition, Julia Timoschenko.
The amendment, which would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will hear the Tymoshenko appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is the political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process has also been suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to ratify it.
