IBM's innovator is entering the second century of his existence.
If anyone wants to find a word that best expresses an IMB strategy, the closest thing to it is probably "long-term."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered to be very modern, even though it was founded over a century ago.
The company's longevity was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He believed in his motto, according to which many of the world's problems can be solved easily if people want to think.
His slogan, "Think!", was the image of the future giant (and the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
In fact, it was the basis of a corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
"For us in IBM, long-term thinking means a constant move to the future.
IBM survived and flourished for a hundred years because it was true to its original values, though it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first 100 years, this has enabled us to transform technology, business, and company.
