Trends in travel prices since 1989
Prior to 1989, only five state travel agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Šedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea, and Autotourist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, the travel agencies of the time were mostly selling tours to the socialist bloc.
As a result, on vacation Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea, on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we were able to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which led to considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to make individual trips to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakia national wanted to go on his own, such as to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise, an individual journey was not possible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to go to the West, but either needed to be in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permission was needed to travel to the West, and it was not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was not possible to get the money (Western currency) to go to the West without a currency permit.
Most of the time, the Czechs spent their vacations at home, leading to a large number of cottages and summer homes, a habit that still exists today.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 leave to the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries all over the world.
The great paradox, which we are no longer aware of, is that, until 1989, we were not able to visit the most popular Croatia today, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990 the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring Western European countries was eliminated, and this led to a massive wave of short trips, mostly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia had no way of enjoying their trips to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists were sleeping in parks in tents, as their income at the time was short for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring in their own food (conserves, salami, etc.) in order to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and after decades, our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income rose, which led to another important event in about 1997.
Since 1997, the increased demand has made it possible for travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, and in comparison with the past, air travel has become incredibly cheap by the ability to order bulk discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs didn't need a visa to go to almost all the developed worlds, except the US, which made our journeys even easier.
The next major event in the history of the post-revolution journeys took place in 2000, and the high demand has led to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been transporting Czech tourists to warm, exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic directions.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs are visiting exotic countries every year!
And another important event in this period, symbolizing our post-revolution development, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States cancelled the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and my country has thus become a permanent member of the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history, in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for the time of their leave abroad, including their cost at their destination.
