Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which is awarding the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book he's written now is unusual, he describes it, quite precisely, as "work on anti-history."
There are few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are few ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions on tactics and combat technology.
It's not so much a book about what was, - he explains - it's a book about what it was like, it's about "the feelings, the impressions, the feelings and the state of the spirit."
The book "Beauty and Pilgrimage" combined the experience of 20 more or less uncharted men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone's gonna go into captivity, lose a hand or a leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives are blinking here like church candles: new ones are added to a lot of others, and some are fading at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of history.
This is also an amendment to the idea that the First World War was just a gravel war on the West Front.
"Beauty and Pilgrimage" is a skillful panorama of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkan, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are hit by bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the start.
War has engendered the lives of these people as a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smokeless gunpowder.
When you're not far from being heard, and you're a woman at home with the kids, will you stay or run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we have to fight in this war.
