Other legislators have not yet been able to make their amendments to the plenary, but not because they have not tried.
The Gudlat amendment was only one of the 68 constitutional amendments that addressed a wide range of issues that had been introduced in that meeting.
Some were duplicative - the same bill was introduced in the House of Representatives and in the Senate - others were minor variations.
There are at least 15 versions of the Balanced Budget amendments in the House of Representatives alone, and there is more about “control over federal expenditures”.
Some of them are also identical, but give their authors, mostly the newly elected Republicans who want to decorate their resumes, an opportunity to brag that they have “promoted” such a proposal.
The Budget Control Act, which was passed in August, required both the House of Representatives and the Senate to vote in favour of the Balanced Budget Amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
