Walls have eyes: How do researchers study you on Facebook?
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremists in Europe, Anders Bering Bravik was a normal guy who spoke his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braiwick, who had confessed to the massacre in Norway in July, which had claimed 77 lives, appeared at his first public court hearing.
Although Braywick could act alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time prepping for an attack on his computer, in touch with the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups in social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We've found it easy to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on the European Cyber Populism of the British DEMOS Research Center.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so big, says Bartlett, that it would be easy for researchers to use the site's promotional tool to identify the necessary population group with scientific certainty -- that marketers have been doing for a number of years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then tipped them off with ads, but instead of showing a new band or a diet, the ads offered the user a poll that included questions about the level of their education, the attitude to violence, and the optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, not even leaving the office.
"This is a brand-new way to do research," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not as impressive: online right-handers are more often male youths who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But all of a sudden, "those who match their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who are just hiding behind the screen."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers, and polytologists use the site to look into everything in the world, from health to social trends in the Laikas, wall posts, and status update.
With more than 800 million active users, adding an average of three entries a day, Facebook's "super-actual information" has created a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the name of the site in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it provides an opportunity to learn about people who cannot be reached on the street with a notebook.
"Before, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to join the party, and they'd never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all of this - you're talking to them directly."
Others say that this site could be used to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her co-workers found that students who discussed their drunken feats on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who didn't talk about it.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as their hostel instructors, can monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates his drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Children's Institute of Research.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook also regularly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
