Climatic problems have slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López's rule in Sinaloa, unemployment and the illegal labour market rose, foreign financing declined, and the economy was weakened.
2011 - The year that will be part of Sinaloa ' s economic history as associated with the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, also referred to as the year of change, which has given rise to high hopes for economic development, but given the adverse climate conditions of the beginning of the year, there has been no growth, but there has been a decline in the main economic development indicators.
Not only have the low temperatures of February led to the loss of millions in the agricultural sector, but they have restricted the growth potential of the public economy, leading to a total decline of 3.6 per cent in economic activity in the first half of the year, largely due to the historic fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to a report on areas affected by seams provided by the Council for Sustainable Rural Development of Mexico, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78,03 per cent were affected, while the remaining 21,07 per cent were partially affected.
The decline in economic activity has led to a constant rise in the state ' s unemployment rate up to November, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters, an accelerated increase in the rate of unemployment, from January to March 55.053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 per cent, and from July to September it continued to grow to 6.19 per cent, a proportion that is more than 74,000 unemployed Sinloa people, an increase of 18.969 more than the first half.
Diminishment of liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa over the course of the year has been overwhelmed by a number of factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, the director of the Department of Economics and Social Science of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be attributed indirectly to the actions taken in public policy.
"What we see now is an increase in unemployment, which is linked to a number of factors, including the loss of market liquidity to limit the resources imposed by the law, which was adopted in Congress to combat money-laundering, as it is not easy for people who are illegally possessing dollars to work with them, invest and use them in something," he said.
Stopped Immigration
Lopez Cervantes said that there was also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad has been restricted in the United States, primarily because of the difficulty of entry, and in the second, because once they enter, they already face a lot of difficulty in finding work, so that a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result, the unemployment rate grows," he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Analysing the Sinaloa labour market is getting worse when we look at the high number of labour-stabilities, according to INEGI, 60,38% of the active population of the state is working without being mentioned as employees in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregularity, a further reminder of the state ' s work is given by low wages; in the state, the lowest wage in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was up to September 5,352 peso, much lower than the national average of 7,375.
FDI reduction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high unemployment rate, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, according to the Department of Finance, was $630,697 from January to July. This represents a decline of 87.74 per cent, compared to $5,143,312 over the same period last year.
For its part, the State Government's Department of Economic Development has recorded only 17,280,000 peso-investment in the year, which has largely been the result of service companies.
Duty
Against the background of the economic downturn, the state government in July requested the approval of a 3-billion-peso loan to be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, at the local level, a total of 2,600 million peso was approved, and until November the debt was not expected in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For businessmen, Mario López Valdez's first year of government demonstrates a lack of government capacity.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, President of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of the various sectors, including the state government itself, during 2011.
"The efficiency of the Sinaloa economy this year has been really low, we have to work hard to get back the positions we lost this year, we have to redouble our efforts in 2012, we have not been able to agree on the efforts of all and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
The slowing down of the economy
López Loredo said that events such as the early freezes this year stopped the state economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“The low size of the economy is the result of a number of events, including the frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy, which is not getting fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services, and, therefore, at the end of the year, we close it below our expectations,” he said.
Revision of heading
Theodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that the state needed to continue its most dynamic productive activity.
“In general, we have found that we have been working on this, we believe that there is a need to develop a long-term programme that will rethink the direction and economic course of the state, and to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Work to be undertaken
President Coparmex stressed the importance of setting the future direction to better guide the Government.
“In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in a number of areas, there is little progress in terms of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term programme,” he said.
He noted that the current Administration had shown progress in its own manner of public policy.
"There are facts that enable us to say that the government is starting to get involved in the work, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the Government is aware that much more needs to be done," he said.
