In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he was not in agreement with the argument of the project in the sense that the federal executive cannot set out the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that, if this had been the case, it would have affected the autonomy of the regulator” and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
Changing analogues to digital signals, one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal, and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transforming into a digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which have not just a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “requests the work of the entire system of public economic governance to include a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the State executive”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the Government, by adopting the decree in question, which in any event affects the competence of the Congress, ensures, in the administrative sphere, the observance of the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he has said.
In Michoacana, analyzing the possibility of counting a "vote-by-vote"
The difference between the first and the second seats in the Governor ' s election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 per cent of the total of 6.074 records.
The possibility of counting a “vote-for-vote” is real, as far as this year's electoral process in Michoacán is concerned, where, according to the Provisional Results Programme (PPP), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 of the 6.774 records.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Institute for Elections (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Saragosa, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Corps approved a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán has not adopted the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, as the State Congress approved the reforms just before the legal time frame for their entry into force in this electoral process, and the Governor, Leonel Godoy Rangel, has not included its publication within the time-limit set out in the Act in the State Official Gazette, stating that he has some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJ) ruled on a constitutional claim made by the local legislature and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform “unvalid and illegal”, as it has no right to “permit or support it”.
In an interview on the possibility of a “vote-for-vote vote”, Maria de los Ángeles Landeral argued that with the adoption of the appropriate principles by the General Council of IWM, it would be possible to present a partial or complete count of the votes by the local electoral authority.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes can be made on the condition that: the results of the records are not the same; there is no record of the balloting and the calculation of the documents in the urn or it is not in the hands of the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, a total recount of the votes in all the urns in the elections may take place when there is a sign that the difference between the presumed winner of the elections in question and the second-best candidate is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or the coalition who put out the second of the candidates in question.
The total recount will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is determined that the difference between the winner and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party, whose candidate has been the second-place candidate, in the event that the ballot boxes, which have been taken into account in the partial recalculation, are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case in Morellia, where, according to PDRP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even if there are 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocols.
