Fujimori was hospitalized again for a medical examination.
Ex-President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday at the State Hospital, and his family doctor told him to check for the loss of muscle in his legs.
Fujimori, 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his administration (1990-2000) suffers from a number of diseases, including language cancer, which has led to his operation four times and is under surveillance.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV channel N that Fujimori would be screened in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of power in his lower extremities.
Aginaga said that in his view Fujimori should be a candidate for the benefit of a pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he didn't want it because he knew he was innocent.
He's had four tests on language cancer, he's lost 18 kilograms of weight, and he's got other diseases, such as a strong erosion gastreet, pancreas cysts, kidney rocks, high blood pressure, and a problem with blood in his legs, a doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007, at the National Police Department of Special Operations.
