Mujika is going to Mexico to fortify political ties
An official delegation led by the President of Uruguay, José Muhika, and made up of a number of ministers and businessmen, will come to Mexico this Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and to start negotiations on the political problems of the region.
Mujika will meet next Wednesday with her Mexican colleague, Felipe Calderon, the most important item in the plan to meet with the political, commercial and Uruguayan communities in Mexico, according to a timetable published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two Presidents in Guadalajara will be “favourable for the exchange of information on political relations between the two nations”, as the South American leadership has published on its website.
According to the local media, Mujica is seeking support for Uruguay in an incident with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy listed the South American country as a tax haven at a G20 meeting in the French city of Canne.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remained tax havens, a statement that had led to Uruguay ' s protest and the withdrawal for his ambassador ' s consultations in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20, a group of the most developed and developing countries since November, and has, in fact, an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Government of Uruguay has in recent years tried to speed up the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements in order to leave the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development's grey list, drawn up from countries that do not enjoy international standards of tax cooperation.
With regard to the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
