MSS announces an obesity gene search program
Social protection leads a study on the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, the protocol “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence”, which will provide an estimate of signs of overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Biochemistry Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietologists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is supported by specialists and postgraduates from the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Centre for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prepared or not) is invited to take part in the MSSI sports centres participating in the study, to the Valley of Mexico City, where every Saturday, from 8 a.m., a test will be carried out with the participation of children.
He stressed that the protocol had begun to run at a sports centre in Cuautemok (West of Mexico) and that, since 8 October, the events had been held at a sports centre in Nesaualcovotl (east of Mexico City).
Once the target of 500 to 600 children has been met, the study will be continued at the Independence Sports Centre (south of Mexico City) and, finally, at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the aim of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics for the development of obesity and to identify risk factors among children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day will be observed, and the main aim is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of 6 and 14, with the permission and supervision of their parents, to complete their individual dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that result in diseases such as diabetes or renal infirmity.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometry of all participants (weight, growth and waist cover), blood pressure and levels of glucose, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify the genes associated with child obesity) would be carried out.
Crus Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in the weight of children.
Medical studies carried out between 1999 and 2006 show that there has been an increase in only 6 years: 77 per cent in the case of boys, 47 per cent in the case of girls; overweight, there has also been a significant increase,” said MSSI.
He said that the validity of the search for markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in their genetic history.
He reported that, on average, he was 65 per cent of the American Indians, 30 per cent of the Europeans, and 5 per cent of the Africans, a condition that affected the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main effect of obesity genetics is the inability of the body to burn the excess of energy that we are consuming (calories) and it is postponed in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, having a dark stride on the neck (matters) and forearms means the risk of a metabolism or even a pre-diabeth.
The information is given in full secrecy, and the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and changes in the way of life that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Crus Lopez explained that there are three main reasons for overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sit-down, or a lack of daily physical activity, a lot of the day at home in front of the TV, and the use of small distances of transport instead of walking.
It is also due to the high use of calories, i.e. the increase in the use of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tams, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with high levels of fat and protein, and the genetic predisposition analysed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Department of Chemistry, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to make a mix of best quality resistant to the environment and temperature.
If the signals sent by the road cover had been given attention, it would have been necessary to renovate about 200,000 holes for each rainy season in the Metropolitan Valley, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Department, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalted road cover is correct, the number of holes can be reduced or reduced to zero.
In his lecture, a technical view of the pits, read in the context of the International Year of Chemistry, states that the laboratory for which it is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mix of properties close to the bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the North, to improve the quality of the roads and thus to resist the formation of a hole.
He explained that the bitumen, the hardest part of the oil, was a sequencing of hydrocarbon molecules, some of it was a high molecular mass, called asphalts, and some of it was a low molecular mass, called maltens, which together provided a road cover for its characteristic viscosity.
The viscosity of the bitumen is the fact that in high-temperatures about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 of its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it stays almost solid, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not permanent, but changes over the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, by a chemical engineer.
The chemist observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible cover, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen made of small rocks, put into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that forms this surface, he said, is sunk in bitumen.
In the case of transport and effort, this helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road surface.
If it was a modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt cover, he added, the last layer, which is called a decomposition layer, made of a small stone, in fact sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt cover and provide for road friction.
As part of the road surface, which will receive and distribute this effort, the wear layer also requires the proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature changes, are also very important for consideration, especially water, he said, because it has a significant effect on the state of asphalt.
When the land is raw, the water penetrates the surface, and it's hard to get out of it, it's softening all the layers of the surface, and so the formation of a hole.
In the formation of a hole, he said, the first thing to erode is a layer of wear and then it will affect the bitumen, but the damage does not happen instantly, a process that should be taken into account in the first signs of a maintenance program.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport is another important factor in the creation of holes, so the thickness of each layer of the surface should always be linked to the transport load and must be guaranteed to meet this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of a hole.
Raphael Herrera said that a lot of bitumen still has to be studied and done, for example, bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help to fix holes lightly and without the use of high temperatures.
