The North Flux, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Line, which links Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with pop.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the band's performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the North Flux, a new gas pipeline that directly links Russia and Germany underwater.
German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fion, and his Dutch colleague, Marta Rütte, together turned the figurative valve controlling the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Under the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million extra cubic meters of gas will be flowing to Western Europe every year through the first 1224 km pipeline, linking the Leningrad Region to the land of Meklenburg-Mexia.
The second pipeline is to be ready at the end of 2012 with a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to the total consumption of France.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already under discussion.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this immense project is a win.
The project met the ferocious resistance of Poland and the Baltic States.
The Northern Flux will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany by avoiding the passage through a third country (Polish or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power, making it more difficult for them to influence Russia, threatening to block access to Western European markets.
At the most stressful moment of the Warsaw debate, it was not possible to compare the North Stream with the new “German-Soviet Pact”, insinuating an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That means the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has been able to reach an understanding of a direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are consuming large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are on the run.
“This gas pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it's a new artery that binds us organically,” said François Fion, opening the gas pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both politically and economically important.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of gas arrival.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipe is made of steel in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left since the Second World War.
"A hundred needed to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, North Flux Press Secretary.
There was also a need to take many steps to protect fauna and flora.
Pipeline is a long metallic snake with a weight of 242 Eiffel towers, without ruptures all over it, without valves, and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project manager abandoned it, because Sweden was not thrilled that a Russian public company would live on its shores forever.
"In the event of an accident, we'll cut off the gas in less than a minute," Jens Müller claims.
So, in the event of a leak, the gas in the gas line will go out.
But this seems unlikely to be the designer of the seams, which are designed to run once every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline will be monitored by a submersible robot that pulls the ship, for external surveillance, as well as by a apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-like apparatus is injected inside a 1 metre-wide pipe and pressed forward with a gas stream.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at 3 meters per second, it provides accurate information on any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed for 50 years without the need for the slightest repairs.
Gas circulation is based on the pressure of the gas.
It is 200 bars on departure and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement the project.
The leader is Gazprom, who owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5 per cent each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9 per cent each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called the North Stream, which was charged with the construction and operation of a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Tsugu in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company for 20 years with the possibility of an extension of the full volume of gas transport.
"Gasprom will pay for the full volume, no matter how much gas will actually be transported," states Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline was provided by 30 per cent of the shareholders and 70 per cent of the bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be Euro7.4 million for two pipelines.
The GDF Suez investment will be about 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will pay off their costs, because Gazprom is taking all the risks.
The gas pipeline is moving from the Baltic Sea to Lubmin on a sandy shore, planted with coniferous trees.
The vents are four and a half meters high and form a gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature, and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into the German gas pipelines.
From last Tuesday, the terminal gets one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million an hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
