Despite the public philanthropy policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% as against 9% for the population as a whole.
Disappointing?
"No," states Eric Blanche, Director General Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of work for disabled people.
"Big progress has been made in 15 years."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two, but three times that."
"But there's still a lot of work to do."
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for a disabled person.
Of these, more are older: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They are more of a low-level student: 80 per cent do not have a Bachelor ' s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, as compared to an average of 38 per cent.
In short, all of these criteria, which make it very difficult to get back to work and which are the core of the problem,” says Christian Grapen, Director General Trempling, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about mentality, which is changing, but too slow.
A April study by the IMS-Entreprendre, commissioned by Cité, found that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability and “represented complete people in carts or mentally or mentally disabled”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from having 6 per cent of disabled workers, as set out in the Act of 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Proof: The number of “obligated” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, fell from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on the company," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also reflects a rise in awareness, in particular in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers, as compared to 82 per cent of organizations with 100 to 199.
